(12. Thoughts on Role Confusion) Tj
T*
(Source: Giles' blog | Published: Wed, 24 Jun 2026 20:15:00 +0000) Tj
T*
(Link: https://www.gilesthomas.com/2026/06/role-confusion) Tj
T*
(The other day, I came across " Prompt Injection as Role Confusion " \( via Simon Willison \).) Tj
T*
(It's a really interesting blog-style version of a paper by Charles Ye, Jasmine Cui and Dylan) Tj
T*
(Hadfield-Menell, where they find that LLMs seem to almost ignore 'role' tags like , or , and) Tj
T*
(instead use the tone of text to infer roles. This seems to explain a lot of jailbreaks. The) Tj
T*
(paper When LLMs are reasoning about their context to work out what tokens they need to generate) Tj
T*
(next, they need to separate out different things: what the system prompt says, what the user) Tj
T*
(says, what the LLM itself has said in the past -- and for recent LLMs, what their own past) Tj
T*
(thoughts have been -- their reasoning traces -- and what they've sent to and received from) Tj
T*
(their tools. These "roles" for each bit of text need to be specified in the context. For) Tj
T*
(example, in a simple chatbot \(say, 2022-vintage\), it might be written up a bit like a) Tj
T*
(transcript : The following is a transcript of a conversation between a user, "User", and an AI) Tj
T*
(bot, "Bot". The bot is helpful and friendly. User: What is the capital of France? Bot: The LLM) Tj
T*
(then starts predicting what would come next \(eg. "The capital of France is Paris"\).) Tj
